    = \n| seat_type               = Capital\n| seat                    = [[Brahmanbaria]]\n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            = \n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 1927.11\n| area_metro_km2          = \n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=tableC01/>\n| population_total        = 2,840,498\n| population_as_of        = 2011 census\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = Bibarian\n| population_demonyms     = \n| population_note         = \n| demographics_type1      = \n| demographics1_footnotes = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| demographics1_title1    = \n| demographics1_info1     = \n| timezone1               = [[Bangladesh Standard Time|BST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +06:00\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in Bangladesh|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = 3400\n| website                 = {{URL|www.brahmanbaria.gov.bd}}\n| footnotes               = \n| blank_name_sec1         = [[Human Development Index|HDI]] (2018)\n| blank_info_sec1         = 0.614<ref name=\"GlobalDataLab\">{{Cite web|url=https://hdi.globaldatalab.org/areadata/shdi/|title=Sub-national HDI - Area Database - Global Data Lab|website=hdi.globaldatalab.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><br/>{{color|#fc0|medium}} \u00b7 [[List of regions of Bangladesh by Human Development Index|7th of 21]]\n| blank_name_sec2         = \n| blank_info_sec2         = \n}}\n'''Brahmanbaria''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ac\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u09b9\u09cd\u09ae\u09a3\u09ac\u09be\u09a1\u09bc\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be}}) is a district in east-central [[Bangladesh]].\n\n== Administration and demographics ==\nBrahmanbaria District, which was included in Comilla district (formerly Tipura district) was established in 1984. The district has 4 municipalities, 39 wards, 97 mahallas, 9 upazilas, 98 union parishads, 1081 moussakas and 1329 villages.\n\nAccording to the [[2011 Bangladesh census]], Brahmanbaria District had 538,937 households and a population of 2,840,498.<ref name=tableC01>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbs.gov.bd/Census2011/Chittagong/Brahmanbaria/Brahmanbaria_C01.pdf|title=Population Census 2011: Brahmanbaria Table C-01|website=Bangladesh Bureau of Statistics|access-date=11 July 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923182905/http://www.bbs.gov.bd/Census2011/Chittagong/Brahmanbaria/Brahmanbaria_C01.pdf|archive-date=23 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Subdivisions ==\nBrahmanbaria district is divided into nine Subdivisions (previously known as [[Administrative divisions of Bangladesh|Thanas]] or only one [[Administrative divisions of Bangladesh|Towns]]) as below:\n*[[Brahmanbaria Sadar Upazila]]\n*[[Ashuganj Upazila]]\n*[[Nasirnagar Upazila]]\n*[[Nabinagar Upazila]]\n*[[Sarail Upazila]]\n*[[Kasba Upazila]]\n*[[Akhaura Upazila]]\n*[[Bancharampur Upazila]]\n*[[Bijoynagar Upazila]]\n\n== Parliament constituencies ==\nThere are six [[Jatiyo Shangshad]]  constituencies in Brahmanbaria district. These constituencies and the [[TVXQ|current]] Members of Parliament are:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bangladesh.gov.bd/|title=\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 (Bangladesh) \u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09a4\u09a5\u09cd\u09af \u09ac\u09be\u09a4\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09a8 - \u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0 - People's Republic of Bangladesh|work=bangladesh.gov.bd}}</ref>\n* National seat no 243 [[Brahmanbaria-1]] (Current MP, Bodruddoza Md. Farhad Hossain)\n* National seat no 244 [[Brahmanbaria-2]] (Current MP, Advocate Abdus Sattar Bhuiyan)\n*[[File:Tornado in Brahmanbaria District, Bangladesh 2013 (2).jpg|thumb]]National seat no 245 [[Brahmanbaria-3]] (Current MP, R. A. M. Obaidul Muktadir Chowdhury)\n* National seat no 246 [[Brahmanbaria-4]] (Current MP, [[Anisul Huq (politician)|Anisul Huq]], Minister of Law)\n* National seat no 247 [[Brahmanbaria-5]] (Current MP, [[Mohammad Ebadul Karim Bulbul]])\n* National seat no 248 [[Brahmanbaria-6]] (Current MP, [[AB Tajul Islam]])\n\n== Economy ==\n{{Infobox economy\n| country    = Brahmanbaria\n| image      = BD Brahmanbaria District locator map.svg\n| image_size = \n| caption    = The Location of Brahmanbaria District on the Map of Bangladesh.\n| currency   = \u09f3 [[Bangladeshi Taka]]\n| fixed exchange = \u09f376 [[Bangladeshi Taka|BDT]] = US$1\n| year       = \n| organs     = \n| gdp        = \n| per capita = \n| poverty    = 30%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://203.112.218.65/WebTestApplication/userfiles/Image/LatestReports/Bangladesh_ZilaUpazila_pov_est_2010.pdf |title=Zila level povmap estimates, 2010 |website=Bangladesh Bureau of Statistics }}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| gini       = \n| hdi        = \n| labour      = 1,800,000\n| occupations = Agricultural, industrial, and service\n| unemployment = 3.8%(2010)\n| average gross salary = \n| gross median = \n| average net salary = \n| net median = \n| industries = Gas, Agriculture, Electricity, Fishing\n| edbr       = \n| revenue    = \n| expenses   = \n| usebelowbox = no\n| presentUS$asdefault = no\n}}\n[[File:Meghna River 1.jpg|thumbnail|Ashuganj Port, on Meghna River will be largest port by 2030.]]\nBrahmanbaria is one of the fastest growing districts in the country. The major industries of Brahmanbaria District have been: agriculture, fishing, power, and natural gas.\n\nThis city has the largest railway junction in the country which is Akhaura.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiarailinfo.com/station/map/akhaura-junction-aka/10943|title=AKA/Akhaura Junction Railway Station Map/Atlas \u2013 India Rail Info|work=India Rail Info}}</ref>\n\n===Power and gas===\n[[File:ORION Group constructed two 100 MW HFO based powerplant. in due time and is supplying the national grid..jpg|thumb|Power plant]]\nBrahmanbaria's Titas gas is important to Bangladesh. Currently the government is drilling new wells.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://energybangla.com/titas-starts-new-well-drilling/|title=Titas Starts New Well Drilling \u2013 Energy Bangla|work=Energy Bangla}}</ref> \n\nIn some other parts of Brahmanbaria, gas was found. It resulted in an abrupt fall in the price of gas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/business/regulator-look-unusual-fall-prices-titas-gas-stocks-170947|title=Regulator to look into unusual fall in prices of Titas Gas stocks|work=The Daily Star}}</ref> Many parts of the country people are using gas in many illegal ways. Now the government is trying to solve that issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2015/nov/24/titas-struggles-remove-illegal-gas-connections|title=Titas struggles to remove illegal gas connections|work=Dhaka Tribune}}</ref>\n\n=== Rail ===\n[[File:Akhaura Railway Station.jpg|thumbnail|Largest railway junction in Bangladesh.]]\n\nThere are about ten railway stations in the district. The country of [[India]] decided to use this district to connect power. The government shipped machines of the Palatana project from Kolkata to Agartala by using the Ashuganj river port on Meghna in Brahmanbaria district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Bangladesh-to-ink-pact-with-India-for-100MW-power-from-Tripura/articleshow/49881868.cms|title=Bangladesh to ink pact with India for 100MW power from Tripura|work=The Times of India}}</ref> To connect with India, government of both [[Bangladesh]] and India is building 15&nbsp;km railway from [[Akhaura Upazila|Akhaura]] to [[Agartala]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/infrastructure/india-bangladesh-business-set-to-grow-through-ports-waterways/articleshow/47599967.cms|title=India, Bangladesh business set to grow through ports, waterways|work=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\nIn 2015 the District of Brahmanbaria, like the rest of Bangladesh, faced problems of road blocks due to political agitation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/77841/CNG-drivers-block-Brahmanbaria-highways|title=CNG drivers block Brahmanbaria highways|date=2 September 2015|work=Prothom Alo}}</ref> It became a terrible problem for regional connectivity as it brought a halt to the road and rail transportation. Luckily the situation did not last very long before being resolved. This region also faced with clashing between two groups. In 2015 a man was killed for facing problems between two groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2015/oct/13/man-killed-brahmanbaria-clash|title=Man killed in Brahmanbaria clash \u2013 Dhaka Tribune|work=dhakatribune.com}}</ref> Former Chief Justice of Bangladesh, [[Surendra Kumar Sinha]] had said  while he was delivering his speech in [[Brahmanbaria]] that smuggling was hurting the national the economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/smuggling-hurting-economy-sk-sinha-199327|title=Smuggling hurting economy: SK Sinha|work=The Daily Star}}</ref> Gold and dollar are going out of the country, he said.\n\nIn April 2020, thousands of people defied COVID 19 lockdown to attend the funeral of a Muslim cleric.<ref>https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/global-virus-deaths-154000-cases-700000-live-updates-200417234910029.html?fbclid=IwAR1sofuUF79fX0dJDB2qnvuHvDti3pU5iVZfKIghUEZa_EyesOxMW6Wz8jI</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nBrahmanbaria District is mostly farmland. But within the district many cities can be found. The capital and largest city is Brahmanbaria. Akhaura and Ashuganj ranks also in top three. Prime minister of Bangladesh gave permission to use Ashuganj Port.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/b-desh-agrees-to-allow-india-use-waterways-to-ashuganj-port-114050300513_1.html|title=B'desh agrees to allow India use waterways to Ashuganj port|author=Press Trust of India|date=3 May 2014|work=business-standard.com}}</ref> In addition, Akhaura Station will be connected to Agartala.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-07-26/news/64880593_1_bangladesh-side-akhaura-bangladesh-counterpart-sheikh-hasina|title=Government approves Rs 1,000 crore for India-Bangladesh rail link|work=timesofindia-economictimes}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Paikpara.jpg|thumb|left|Brahmanbaria city neighbourhood]]\nBrahmanbaria was a part of '''Samatata''' Janapada of the ancient [[Bengal]]. The first and temporary capital of [[Isa Khan]] was at Sarail,<ref name=bpedia>{{cite web|author=AA Sheikh Md Asrarul Hoque Chisti|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Isa_Khan|title=Isa Khan|publisher=[[Banglapedia]]: The National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh, [[Asiatic Society]] of Bangladesh, [[Dhaka]]|accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> located at 10 km north of Brahmanbaria Town. Brahmanbaria was made one of the 3 Sub-divisions of [[Comilla]] District by the British rulers in 1790.<ref>{{cite book|last=Siddiqi|first=Mamun|year=2012|chapter=Comilla District|chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Comilla_District|editor1-last=Islam|editor1-first=Sirajul|editor1-link=Sirajul Islam|editor2-last=Jamal|editor2-first=Ahmed A.|title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh|edition=Second|publisher=Asiatic Society of Bangladesh}}</ref> Brahmanbaria Municipality was established in 1868.It became part of [[East Pakistan]] in 1947 which eventually became independent [[Bangladesh]] in 1971. \n\nDuring the Mughal era, Brahmanbaria was famous for producing quality cloth [[Muslin]].<ref name=\"Eaton1996\">{{citation |last=Eaton |first=Richard Maxwell |date=1996 |title=The Rise of Islam and the Bengal Frontier, 1204\u20131760 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gKhChF3yAOUC&pg=PA202 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-20507-9 |page=202}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Karim |first=Abdul |date=2012 |chapter=Muslin |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Muslin |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring 19th century, Brahmanbaria produced great nationalist leaders like Nawab Syed Shamsul Huda, who became president of [[All India Muslim League]] in 1921, and Barrister Abdur Rasul, a front ranking leader of [[Indian National Congress]]. When the swadeshi movement began in the wake of the partition of Bengal (1905), Brahmanbaria born revolutionary Ullaskar Datta (Aviram) was convicted for throwing bomb explosion and was deported to the Andamans.\n\nUpon encouragement of [[Oli Ahad]], a pioneer [[Language Movement]] leder who hailed from Brahmanbaria, the movement obtained momentum in this district in 1952.<ref name=\"BD\">{{cite web|url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2012/10/20/language-warrior-oli-ahad-dead |title=Language warrior Oli Ahad dead|publisher=bdnews24|accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"DS\">{{cite news|title=Oli Ahad no more|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/-details.php?nid=254689|accessdate=2012-10-21|newspaper=The Daily Star|date=21 October 2012|location=Dhaka, Bangladesh|page=1}}</ref>\n\nDuring the War of Liberation in 1971, [[Bir Sreshtha]] Mohammad Mostafa Kamal faced a heroic death in an encounter with Pakistan Army at Daruin of Akhaura in Brahmanbaria district.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |last1=Chandan|first1=Md Shahnawaz Khan|title=A Hero's Tale|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/a-heros-tale-32545 |work=The Daily Star |access-date=18 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a pot of 200-year-old coins was found in District's [[Akhaura Upazila]]. There were nearly 500 coins at the Temple of Durga in Mogra Union. The coins contained the image of British Queen Elizabeth-I and were from 1804, 1814 and 1836. Police said the coins were handed over to archaeology department.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2015/aug/30/200-year-old-coins-recovered|title=200-year-old coins recovered|work=Dhaka Tribune}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.brahmanbaria.gov.bd/}}\n\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* {{Brahmanbaria zela blog|http://www.bbariafinder.com/}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title = Destinations from Brahmanbaria District\n|Northwest = [[Kishoreganj District]]\n|North     = [[Habiganj District]]\n|Northeast = ([[India]])\n|West      = [[Dhaka District]]\n|Centre    = Brahmanbaria District\n|East      = ([[Agartala]], India)\n|Southwest = [[Narayanganj]]\n|South     = [[Comilla District]]\n|Southeast = ([[India]])\n}}\n\n{{Divisions and districts of Bangladesh}}\n\n[[Category:Brahmanbaria District| ]]\n[[Category:Districts of Chittagong Division]]\n[[Category:Districts of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:1860 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{about |Brahmanbaria District|the city or capital of Brahmanbaria District|Brahmanbaria}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2016}}\n{{original research|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Brahmanbaria\n| native_name             = \u09ac\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u09b9\u09cd\u09ae\u09a3\u09ac\u09be\u09a1\u09bc\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\n| native_name_lang        = bn<!-- ISO 639-1 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| official_name            = \n| type                    = [[Districts of Bangladesh|District]]\n| image_skyline           = \n| imagesize               = \n| image